commentText: Hello from Spain! I‚Äôd like to share my humble opinion on the current situation. In a nutshell, the macroeconomy is doing well, but the microeconomy is struggling.  On the macroeconomic side, we have positive indicators: strong GDP growth, rising exports, a booming tourism sector, and decreasing unemployment rates. We also have the good fortune of receiving migration from Latin America, which shares both our language and much of our culture. This has allowed for smoother social integration compared to other countries where migration often generates more social conflict. In fact, migration to Spain from non-Latin American regions tends to present greater challenges.  However, on the microeconomic front, things are more challenging. Wages often do not match the rising cost of living, particularly affecting younger generations. Housing prices and rental costs have skyrocketed, making access to affordable housing increasingly difficult.  That‚Äôs the big picture from here‚Äîthank you for the insightful video!

commentText: You don't understand Spain's politics or economy. This news is false, and I'm going to explain why.  GDP growth driven by employment rather than productivity  GDP can grow either through increased employment or higher productivity. In Spain, growth has been more reliant on job creation rather than productivity improvement.  The expansion of GDP since 2019 is largely due to the increase in employment among foreign workers.  Of the 1.75 million new jobs created in the last five years, only 388,000 went to Spaniards, while 1.35 million were taken by foreigners. Virtually all GDP growth has been captured by foreign workers. Real incomes of Spaniards have remained stagnant since 2019.  Although the overall economy is advancing, the well-being of native citizens has not significantly improved. Growth benefits immigrants, but many Spaniards remain in the same economic situation as five years ago.

commentText: Hey, going to give my two cents on this. Although GDP may be growing, the cost of living is rising insanely quickly. Spain used to have a very low cost of living, and therefore not very high salaries. Salaries have stayed the same, but the cost of living has gone up exponentially. Living in Madrid or Barcelona is as expensive if not more than in places like London, but salaries are much lower.  Also, a lot of people have said this, but the government is cheating a lot on its reporting of the economy. Many definitions have been changed, such as that for "employed" people (if you work a seasonal job 3 months a year you are now classified as fully employed), and in general the INE has come under a lot of scrutiny because its overblowing most statistics. Keep in mind, even with these wrong statistics unemployment is completely unsustainable. You also have a bunch of large companies which bring in a lot of wealth leaving the country (i.e: Ferrovial).  I get that this is simply a macro analysis of the Spanish economy, and thats fine. I just feel that its worth to mention that this huge growth is occurring within the context of a hugely inefficient government. The weird thing about this economic growth is that it somehow manages to happen while businesses are being stifled and living standards are getting worse.

Imagine that a loaf of bread costs 0.80 in Switzerland and 1.20 in Spain "for example", but in Switzerland the average salary is 3,000 and in Spain 1,200... the difference is greater if you divide the price in each country by the salary and compare it. Even if a loaf of bread in Switzerland were worth 2 euros and in Spain 1, it would still be favorable to Switzerland, since it is 2 times the price of the product compensated by a salary 3 times higher (this is a crude example)
 
 Another factor is the low accessibility to housing...prices increase, confidence in the security of "house raider" homes, or the increase in taxes despite the fact that salaries do not rise to the same level, is worrying. We see a worsening in many public services, we see an increase in taxes, but we do not see an improvement at street level in our lifestyle...Less purchasing power, lower salaries, higher taxes, concern about pensions, lack of police resources to combat crime and bad inmigration "In fact, 2 police officers who did not have adequate vehicles or bulletproof vests have died fighting drug trafficking", superfluous expenses in infrastructure, problems with the road and highway network are very noticeable. Many of these factors are not reflected in the study and are elements that, although they do not reflect the performance of an economy, do reflect the impact of the economy on our lifestyles.
 
 On the other hand, if the per capita income is higher, it is only on paper, since we do not appreciate that there is a direct relationship between that indicator and the consumption capacity of our pockets...in other words, it is like saying that if there are two fried chickens, and only two people, statistically we have both eaten a chicken. The reality is that this year there are 2 chickens, but we continue eating half a chicken each.
 
 Cheers!!

commentText: I‚Äôm Spanish, and I can tell you there are several reasons for this. Even though the economy has grown, the vast majority of people haven‚Äôt seen an improvement in their purchasing power due to rising prices. Even if your salary had increased at the same rate as inflation (which is usually not the case), the fact that income taxes haven‚Äôt been adjusted for inflation means you actually end up with less purchasing power.  Additionally, we‚Äôve experienced a higher cumulative inflation for last years that hasn‚Äôt been reflected in wage increases. On top of that, some macroeconomic data is distorted due to changes in how it's calculated. For example, unemployment figures don‚Äôt include temporary workers who aren‚Äôt currently employed, nor do they account for actual hours worked (as there are more part-time jobs).  Lastly, inflation statistics don‚Äôt fully reflect the significant rise in housing costs, which has had a major impact on people's financial situation.

commentText: I think one of the main indicators of people's discontent is the ratio between the mode salary (the salary range that repeats the most) and the price of houses. That's one thing that is hardly talked about, and it seems to be the most important indicator, because in rents and mortages is where you put the greatest chunk of your monthly income. If you're paying lets say... more than 33% of your income just for the housing (rent or mortage), then it is a lot. Places like the big cities of Spain (Madrid, Barcelona,...), along with the coastline towns have seen a huge jump in housing prices because we have a lot of people coming from all over Europe with high wages that buy houses and help the house prices to rise, also creating a big pressure in the housing market. Maybe that's one of the most important issues with the people's discontent. If people are losing economic power due to a sharp increase in the cost of living, how can it be said that the country's economy is improving? ü§î

videoTitle: If Spain is the world‚Äôs best economy, why are they so unhappy?
videoDescription: Advertising sponsor: Get access to global coverage at an exclusive 20% discount at https://economist.com/moneymacro If you ...
commentText: Some thoughts from a Spaniard, you already touched on most of these throughout the video, but I hope I can add something:  The botched recovery from the 2008 GFC made us very negative about the economy. Our purchasing power has barely recovered since 2008 after inflation, and well, you can see the effects on the graph you posted about the "feelings" on the Spanish economy.  Then there was the recent inflationary crisis, which has affected Spanish families a lot. And this has a severe impact on our perception of the economy, similarly to how it happened in the US. For instance, prices of some foods have gone up like 50% or more. Sure, "technically" this is not a big deal because this was only a small part of our expenses, but seeing the high prices every time you go to the supermarket will affect your vision of the economy. Salaries have also increased but, well, everyone expects their salary to increase with time.  A third thing, partially related, is the housing crisis. Another global phenomenon, but it has hit some areas in Spain hard, plus, with Spanish families coming from a worse position (compared to, say, Dutch families) they are struggling a lot more to cope with the rent increases.  Like you mentioned, again, this was a good year, but what is a 3% increase to a median family. Supposing even that small percentage change affected them when you account for inflation and all, it really is barely noticeable. It's just one year, we might be the best performing economy in how we improved, but unless we see this go on for 4+ years, I don't think the "feelings" about the economy will change much.  Lastly, the fact that a large part of the change was driven by immigration is also a concern. NOT about immigration itself (that's another topic) but about the sustainability of the growth. We have one of the lowest fertility rates in Europe, which makes our pension system one of the least sustainable in the continent. Immigration was particularly high due to political/economic troubles in Argentina and Venezuela, for instance, but this won't go on forever. Many people who want to leave those countries due to the recent troubles already left, and while a constant trickle of immigration from Latin America is expected to continue, the immigration rate may go down to previous levels, stifling the economic growth (and worsening our struggles with an aging population).  So, yes, we had a great year. But it was just a year. If it continues, which is a big "if", Spain might earn the right to call itself the "best" economy in the world, but I will hold my enthusiasm.

videoTitle: The Brutal Reality of the Tech Job Market
videoDescription: The tech job market right now is brutal. Layoffs, endless applications, and constant rejections. It feels impossible to land an offer.
commentText: I've come to the conclusion that I no longer want to chase after a language or framework. This changes all the time. I've also decided that I will no longer subject myself to being treated like a commodity at a cattle auction. In the end, all of this is designed to make you accept doing more for less. I think at some point we give in and accept unrealistic things because the "market demands it," or the influencer you follow or the group of followers in the bubble you're in dictates that this is the culture, technology, or method to be adopted. Yes, I went through a financial setback and had to accept working in other segments. But that didn't kill my desire to work with software. Today, I think the path is to work as an entrepreneur and consultant for small businesses, creating solutions for the region you live in or where you can work without creating a burden on your life. Another mistake I see is the industrialization of the IT workforce. We didn't start that way; we started in a garage or on a small project; we're not cattle.

commentText: Everyone who is saying usa is not easiest to get into and has discrimination should know some things. As someone who has done extensive research on this topic and actually made contact with people who are doing their post graduation in these countries. What he is saying is the absolute truth USA is the easiest to get into for medical pg. Even in australia you won't get any specialisation of your choice even if you clear both amc exams , the specialities you get are only the seats leftover after all Aussie graduates are taken (doctors are less in australia but so are colleges that produce them)  - and there are few specialities like emergency medicine left for imgs. As of UK plab isn't ur license to specialisation in the uk it is just an exam you pass to work in UK after clearing plab you still have to pass mrcp / mrcog / mrcs .etc which 70% people who are doctors in the UK fail to pass. Not to mention the job scarcity even after clearing plab 1 and plab 2 due to inflation. The salary in nhs is barely liveable in uk , laymen get paid more than doctors in uk. So yes usa has the least discrimination against foreign doctors and the only hurdle is usmle atleast they guarantee a job in specialities like internal medicine , family medicine and emergency medicine if you perform well in usmle and play your cards right from the start.

commentText: Program AI to auto generate resumes for you.  You should have thousands of different resume versions.  Have it collect data for what specific versions get responses.  Have the AI automatically apply and spam those resumes to MILLIONS of job postings and boards.  When you track which ones finally get responses, you can have AI analyze the data collected.  Then have that go into an evolutionary algorithm to increase fitness to the resume versions that actually generated responses.  After a few thousand generations, your AI should have finely tuned optimal resume versions that generate tons of responses.  Now, for the interview and whiteboard problems, this is where google glass comes in.  There's way to generate 'gray" references and experience too.  Also there shouldn't be ANY particular tech stack, framework, or toolchain out there that you DON'T claim to be an absolute EXPERT in.  AI can help you through faking it till you make it.  There's no reason for you to sell yourself short, given the amount of assistance AI can provide with all those different "skills"

videoTitle: Tech Job Market in 2025: What‚Äôs Next?
videoDescription: The tech job market has faced major layoffs since 2022, with lasting effects in 2023 and 2024. But is 2025 bringing a recovery?
commentText: People blame AI for the mass layoffs in software engineering, but honestly, the bigger factor is H1B.  There are about 1.2 million software engineers working in the U.S. That number hasn‚Äôt really changed much over the last decade. So despite all the layoffs, it‚Äôs not that software engineering is going away‚Äîthe jobs are still here. What‚Äôs actually changing is who‚Äôs holding those jobs.  Right now, there are roughly 600,000 active H1B visa holders working across 50,000 companies in the U.S. About two-thirds of them are in tech, mostly in software engineering. That means around 400,000 of the 1.2 million software engineers in this country are H1B workers.  Now, the cap on new H1B visas is 85,000 per year, but there‚Äôs no cap on renewals. So while domestic engineers are getting laid off or locked out of entry-level roles, the number of active H1B engineers just keeps growing.  If you do the math, over the past 8 to 10 years, about 4 to 5 percent of the domestic software workforce has been replaced each year. But that percentage is getting worse. With so many layoffs and people leaving the field, there are maybe 800,000 American engineers left. So if 55,000 new H1Bs are still coming in each year, that‚Äôs more like 7 to 8 percent of what's left being replaced annually.  Take Microsoft for example. They‚Äôve gone through multiple rounds of layoffs this year, but also applied for over 6,000 new H1B slots. That‚Äôs not unusual either‚Äîtons of companies are doing the same.  Now, my opinion: The H1B program was supposed to be a way to bring over highly specialized talent in cases where the U.S. was lacking. It was never meant to be a tool for replacing domestic professionals with cheap labor. But that‚Äôs exactly how it‚Äôs being used.  And we‚Äôre seeing the results. Code quality is dropping. Technical debt is piling up. Onboarding is slower, product velocity is declining, and morale is shot. Engineers, both domestic and foreign, are burning out. The whole thing is starting to feel like a bubble. And at some point, it‚Äôs going to pop.
